In Sweden, yellow brain fungus was burnt to protect against evil spirits.

results.notes:
This collection was growing on the side of a gravel road on the edge of a young pitch pine thicket. In the past this general area has given rise to a number of different late summer and fall mushrooms, notably Tricholoma aff. albobrunneum of obs 261106. The somewhat scaly cap was light pinkish-brown, the color of a diluted hot chocolate drink.
This collection was saved and sampled for DNA (ITS).
DNA sequencing results & discussion (posted on 7-May-22):
A full-length nrITS sequence was obtained from this collection. The reads show a single point of heterogeneity ~80 characters into ITS1 region at a C-homopolymer. It’s a simple “echo” pattern due to a single-base frameshift, leading to two haplotypes that are different in length by 1 character (Hap-2 has an extra C in the homopolymer) but are otherwise identical. Hence, the final sequence is technically a joined contig, although I resolved the heterogeneity in the reverse read all the way to the ITS1F primer in SSU.
This is Hydnellum scabrosum by ITS, as indicated by the highly similar GenBank accessions linked to a couple of recently published published papers on Hydnellum, Phellodon and Sarcodon. Case closed.

Spores: mostly almond shaped, finely roughened.
